BSGatlas-gene-4174 "-glucosyltransferase has been isolated by Glaser and Burger in 1964
|CITS: [14245359]|. At that time it was shown that this enzyme transfers glucosyl moieties from UDP-glucose to
the hydroxyl residues at carbon 2 of the glycerol-phosphate units of teichoic acid.
It was already recognized that this presents only the simplest teichoic acid structure, and that teichoic acids
vary in the nature and number of glycosyl residues attached to them |CITS: [13966000]|.

Later work performed by Brooks et al showed that the enzyme was present in the cell in two forms:
During the initial growth phase it was  found predominantly in a soluble form in the cytoplasm , but  during growth
it gradually shifted towards an insluble, membrane-bound form |CITS: [4327509]|.

More recent genetic work has linked the enzyme with the |FRAME: BSU35730| gene, based on sequence analysis
|CITS: [1906926]|. Even though mutations in |FRAME: BSU35730| have confirmed its role, the enzyme has not been
purified and characterized in detail yet."

BSGatlas-gene-4478 "<b>General Background</b>

Wall teichoic acids, as well as type I and IV lipoteichoic acids, are modified with |FRAME: D-ALANINE| residues, and the enzymes required for this process are encoded by the <i>dltABCD</i> operon |CITS: [1385594]|.

The process starts in the cytoplasm, where |FRAME: EC-6.2.1.M5| (DltA) activates |FRAME: D-ALANINE| using ATP to form a high-energy |FRAME: CPD-19306| intermediate and subsequently transfers it to the phosphopantheinyl prosthetic group of the |FRAME: D-alanine-carrier-protein| (DltC) |CITS: [18847223][18784082][19324056]|.

The product of the DltD gene contains a single putative N-terminal transmembrane helix and a large globular domain. While the exact activity of the enzyme is still not well understood, the gene was cloned and sequenced from |FRAME: TAX-1582|, and a mutant was constructed by insertional mutagenesis. The mutant lost the ability to incorporate D-alanine into lipoteichoic acids, a defect that could be complemented by the expression of an intact version of the gene |CITS: [10781555]|.

The protein was shown to bind to DltC and to possess a thioesterase activity, and thus it was suggested that it may catalyze the final D-alanyl transfer from DltC to teichoic acid. However this could not be demonstrated <i>in vitro</i> |CITS: [10781555]|.

The discovery of substantial amounts of |FRAME: 1-Phosphatidyl-2-O-D-Ala-Glycerol| in lipid lysate from |FRAME: TAX-1423| |CITS: [26998233]| has led to a new hypothesis. According to this hypothesis, DltD may catalyze the transfer of DltC-bound D-alanyl group to |FRAME: L-1-PHOSPHATIDYL-GLYCEROL phosphatidylglycerol| in the bacterial membrane by a thermodynamically spontaneous esterification reaction. |FRAME: 1-Phosphatidyl-2-O-D-Ala-Glycerol| in turn may serve as the lipid intermediate for subsequent D-alanylation of teichoic acids, catalyzed by DltB |CITS: [27134729]|.

<b>About This enzyme</b>

The <i>dlt</i> operon of |FRAME: TAX-224308| was discovered based on its similarity to the genes from |FRAME: TAX-1582| |CITS: [7797557]|. Each of the four genes was inactivated, and analysis of the mutants confirmed that they lacked |FRAME: D-ALANINE| in both their lipoteichoic acids and their wall teichoic acids |CITS: [7797557]|."

BSGatlas-gene-4477 "<b>General Background</b>

Wall teichoic acids, as well as type I and IV lipoteichoic acids, are modified with |FRAME: D-ALANINE| residues, and the enzymes required for this process are encoded by the <i>dltABCD</i> operon |CITS: [1385594]|.

The process starts in the cytoplasm, where |FRAME: EC-6.2.1.M5| (DltA) activates |FRAME: D-ALANINE| using ATP to form a high-energy |FRAME: CPD-19306| intermediate and subsequently transfers it to the phosphopantheinyl prosthetic group of the |FRAME: D-alanine-carrier-protein| (DltC) |CITS: [18847223][18784082][19324056]|.

The product of the DltD gene contains a single putative N-terminal transmembrane helix and a large globular domain. While the exact activity of the enzyme is still not well understood, the gene was cloned and sequenced from |FRAME: TAX-1582|, and a mutant was constructed by insertional mutagenesis. The mutant lost the ability to incorporate D-alanine into lipoteichoic acids, a defect that could be complemented by the expression of an intact version of the gene |CITS: [10781555]|.

The protein was shown to bind to DltC and to possess a thioesterase activity, and thus it was suggested that it may catalyze the final D-alanyl transfer from DltC to teichoic acid. However this could not be demonstrated <i>in vitro</i> |CITS: [10781555]|.

The discovery of substantial amounts of |FRAME: 1-Phosphatidyl-2-O-D-Ala-Glycerol| in lipid lysate from |FRAME: TAX-1423| |CITS: [26998233]| has led to a new hypothesis. According to this hypothesis, DltD may catalyze the transfer of DltC-bound D-alanyl group to |FRAME: L-1-PHOSPHATIDYL-GLYCEROL phosphatidylglycerol| in the bacterial membrane by a thermodynamically spontaneous esterification reaction. |FRAME: 1-Phosphatidyl-2-O-D-Ala-Glycerol| in turn may serve as the lipid intermediate for subsequent D-alanylation of teichoic acids, catalyzed by DltB |CITS: [27134729]|.

<b>About This enzyme</b>

The <i>dlt</i> operon of |FRAME: TAX-224308| was discovered based on its similarity to the genes from |FRAME: TAX-1582| |CITS: [7797557]|. Each of the four genes was inactivated, and analysis of the mutants confirmed that they lacked |FRAME: D-ALANINE| in both their lipoteichoic acids and their wall teichoic acids |CITS: [7797557]|.

The |FRAME: BSU38500| and |FRAME: BSU38520| genes of |FRAME: TAX-224308| were cloned with a C-terminal His<sub>6</sub> tag and expressed in |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant proteins were purified to homogeneity |CITS: [15955059]|. The <i>apo</i> DltC protein was efficiently modified to a <i>holo</i> form by both AcpS (the PPTase of primary metabolism) and Sfp (the PPTase of secondary metabolism).  The purified DltA protein activated only |FRAME: D-ALANINE|, and was rather specific for the D-alanyl-carrier protein (it has some activity with the fatty acid ACP, but the Km for that substrate is in the mM range) |CITS: [15955059]|.

Unlike the <i>E. coli</i> enzyme, <i>B. subtilis</i> NagB is monomeric and not allosterically regulated |CITS: [15755726]|.

BSGatlas-gene-3930 "<i>B. subtilis</i> is able to grow using |FRAME: CPD-8050| as its sole carbon source. In order to identify the enzyme(s) that operate on this compound, the genome was analyzed for genes paralogous to |FRAME: BSU39700|, which encodes |FRAME: CPLX-8649|.
Seven such genes were identified, and two of them were prominently expressed when the cells were grown on medium containing |FRAME: CPD-8050|. The two genes, |FRAME: BSU33530| and |FRAME: BSU10850|, were cloned in |FRAME:TAX-562| as C-terminally His<sub>6</sub>-tagged fusion proteins, and the recombinant proteins were purified |CITS: [20133360]|.

Both proteins were shown to encode a functional |FRAME: CPD-8050| dehydrogenase enzyme. |FRAME: BSU10850| encodes a catabolic NAD+-dependent enzyme, while |FRAME: BSU33530| encodes a presumably biosynthetic NADP+-dependent enzyme |CITS: [20133360]|. Both enzymes possess a much reduced activity with |FRAME: MYO-INOSITOL|.

Inactivation of |FRAME: BSU10850|, but not |FRAME: BSU33530|, abolished growth on |FRAME: CPD-8050| |CITS: [20133360]|."

BSGatlas-gene-727 "|FRAME: BSU05900-MONOMER ""Thiamine monophosphate kinase""| (ThiL) catalyzes the final step in thiamin biosynthesis, the phosphorylation of |FRAME: THIAMINE-P| to |FRAME: THIAMINE-PYROPHOSPHATE|, the biologically active form |CITS: [4567662][4550824][6284709][9188462]|.

Deletion of the |FRAME: BSU05900| gene in |FRAME: TAX-1423| did not generate the expected thiamin auxotroph phenotype, but instead generated a thiamin bradytroph that grew to near-wild-type levels on minimal medium |CITS: [16291685]|. The authors speculated that the reason is that a bypass route, similar to that operating in eukaryotes, can compensate for the thiL activity. In this route the phosphate is removed (by an unknown enzyme) from |FRAME: THIAMINE-P|, generating |FRAME: THIAMINE|, which is then double-phosphorylated by |FRAME: BSU15800|, producing |FRAME: THIAMINE-PYROPHOSPHATE| (see |FRAME: PWY-6898|). To prove this theory, a double mutant of both |FRAME: BSU05900| and |FRAME: BSU15800| was constructed. This mutant could grow on minimal media only in the presence of |FRAME: THIAMINE-PYROPHOSPHATE|, and addition of either |FRAME: THIAMINE| or |FRAME: THIAMINE-P| failed to restore growth |CITS: [16291685]|."
BSGatlas-gene-1233 "|FRAME: BSU10250| double mutant is unable to grow in minimal medium either in the presence or absence of lipoate. In addition, introduction of |FRAME: BSU10250| restores growth of E. coli &Delta"
BSGatlas-gene-1394 "|FRAME: BSU11710-MONOMER ""Hydroxymethylpyrimidine kinase""| is a bifunctional enzyme that catalyzes the phosphorylation of both |FRAME: HMP| (HMP) and |FRAME: AMINO-HYDROXYMETHYL-METHYL-PYR-P|, participating both <i>de novo</i> synthesis and slavage of thiamin.

The |FRAME: BSU11710| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423|, which encodes the enzyme, was cloned and overexpressed in E. coli, and the recombinant protein was purified and characterized |CITS: [14973012]|. The purified enzyme catalyzed both phosphorylation reactions."
BSGatlas-gene-2849 "|FRAME: BSU24270-MONOMER| (Dxs) catalyzes the thiamin diphosphate-dependent reaction that condenses
pyruvate and D-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate to yield |FRAME: DEOXYXYLULOSE-5P| |CITS: [17458547]|. This is the first, rate-limiting step in the |FRAME: NONMEVIPP-PWY| of isoprenoid biosynthesis, and is believed to feed into the pyridoxal 5-phosphate (vitamin B6) and thiamin (vitamin B1) biosynthesis pathways. 

Overexpression of <i>dxs</i> resulted in a yield of isoprene that was 40% over that produced by the wild-type strain |CITS: [21296950]|. 

A study of the |FRAME: TAX-1423| enzyme suggested that it may not be involved in pyridoxal 5-phosphate biosynthesis |CITS: [12882400]|. A linkage between Dxs and thiamin biosynthesis has been established in other organisms |CITS: [15292217]| but not yet in B. subtilis.

BSGatlas-gene-1233 "|FRAME: BSU24530| &Delta"
BSGatlas-gene-4452 "|FRAME: BSU38290-MONOMER ""Thiamine-phosphate diphosphorylase""| (ThiE) catalyzes an important step in the <i>de novo</i> pathway of |FRAME: THIAMINE-PYROPHOSPHATE| biosynthesis, the coupling of the two moieties of thiamin, a thiazole (|FRAME: CPD-13576|) and a pyrimidine (|FRAME: AMINO-HYDROXYMETHYL-METHYLPYRIMIDINE-PP|), forming |FRAME: THIAMINE-P| |CITS: [JAMCHEMSOC1172351]|.

In addition, the enzyme may catalyze a similar reaction in a slavage pathway, where it couples |FRAME: THZ-P| to the pyrimidine moiety.

While most of the research on ThiE was performed with the E. coli enzyme, a genetic screen designed to identify |FRAME: TAX-1423| genes that participate in thiamin metabolism identifed the |FRAME: BSU38290| gene |CITS: [15292217]|. The crystal structure of the |FRAME: TAX-1423| enzyme complexed with the reaction products thiamin phosphate and diphosphate has been determined |CITS: [10350464]|. The structure and other mechanistic studies are consistent with a reaction mechanism involving the ionization of |FRAME:AMINO-HYDROXYMETHYL-METHYLPYRIMIDINE-PP| at the active site to give the pyrimidine carbocation. The reaction is completed by trapping of the carbocation by the thiazole followed by product dissociation |CITS: [10350464]|.
"
BSGatlas-gene-1221 "|FRAME: EC-4.99.1.1|, catalyzes the insertion of Fe<sup>2+</sup> into |FRAME: PROTOPORPHYRIN_IX|. The |FRAME: BSU10130| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423| was thought to catalyze the reaction. The gene was cloned and expressed in |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified. The enzyme was found to be a monomeric and water-soluble, and could incorporate not only Fe<sup>2+</sup> but also Zn<sup>2+</sup> and Cu<sup>2+</sup> into protoporphyrin IX |CITS: [8119288]|. Subsequent studies showed that Tyr13 determines the metal specificity of the enzyme |CITS: [21052751][23097001]|.

However, later studies have shown that the <i>in vivo</i> substrate of the enzyme from Gram-positive bacteria is not |FRAME: PROTOPORPHYRIN_IX| but |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRIN_III| |CITS: [25646457]|. For example, the Km of the enzyme from |FRAME: TAX-1773| for coproporphyrin III is over 60-fold lower than its Km for protoporphyrin IX. In the hand of these authors, the activity of the |FRAME: TAX-1423| enzyme with protoporphyrin IX was too low to measure.

The crystal structure of the enzyme was determined at 1.9 &Aring"
BSGatlas-gene-1233 "|FRAME: EG11591| &Delta"
BSGatlas-gene-1233 "|FRAME: EG11796| double mutants |CITS: [21338420]|. 

The gene was cloned with a hexahistidine-tag, expressed in E. coli and purified to homogeneity. It was shown that in the absence of an acceptor domain the enzyme formed both ocanoyl-adenylate and lipoyl-adenylate intermediates. Upon addition of suitable acceptors, the enzyme modified the lipoate-binding components of both the glycine-cleavage system and the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex with either lipoate and octanoates |CITS: [21338420]|.

While the activity of |FRAME: BSU10250| is negatively influenced by mutations in |FRAME: G-14913|, scavenging of external lipoate is fully functional in a &Delta"
BSGatlas-gene-1233 "|FRAME: TAX-1423| cells lacking both |FRAME: BSU32330| and |FRAME: BSU24530| are able to grow with exogenous lipoate, indicating that the organism posseses the ability to salvage lipoate.
The sole lipoate slavage enzyme in |FRAME: TAX-1423| is encoded by |FRAME: BSU10250|, which is 33% identical to E. coli |FRAME: EG11796| |CITS: [21338420]|.

BSGatlas-gene-1296 "|FRAME: TAX-1423| is able to grow using |FRAME: CPD-8050| as its sole carbon source. In order to identify the enzyme(s) that operate on this compound, the genome was analyzed for genes paralogous to |FRAME: BSU39700|, which encodes |FRAME: CPLX-8649|.
Seven such genes were identified, and two of them were prominently expressed when the cells were grown on medium containing |FRAME: CPD-8050|. The two genes, |FRAME: BSU33530| and |FRAME: BSU10850|, were cloned in |FRAME:TAX-562| as C-terminally His<sub>6</sub>-tagged fusion proteins, and the recombinant proteins were purified |CITS: [20133360]|.

Both proteins were shown to encode a functional |FRAME: CPD-8050| dehydrogenase enzyme. |FRAME: BSU10850| encodes a catabolic NAD+-dependent enzyme, while |FRAME: BSU33530| encodes a presumably biosynthetic NADP+-dependent enzyme |CITS: [20133360]|. Both enzymes possess a much reduced activity with |FRAME: MYO-INOSITOL|.

Inactivation of |FRAME: BSU10850|, but not |FRAME: BSU33530|, abolished growth on |FRAME: CPD-8050| |CITS: [20133360]|."
BSGatlas-gene-3345 "|FRAME: TAX-1423| produces two &alpha"
BSGatlas-gene-3380 "|FRAME: TAX-1423| synthesizes an |FRAME: BSU28810-MONOMER| enzyme encoded by the |FRAME: BSU28810| gene |CITS: [9183009]|. The gene is monocistronic and is transcribed from sigma(A)-like promoter. Expression is induced by arabinose and arabinan and is repressed by glucose. The induction mechanism is mediated through negative control by the key regulator of arabinose metabolism, AraR |CITS: [14973026]|.

The gene was cloned with a His6-tag fused to the C-terminus and expressed in E. coli. The recombinant protein, which is extracellular in its native host, was secreted to the periplasmic space and correctly processed by the E. coli signal peptidase. The recombinant protein was purified to homogeneity |CITS: [15556708]|.

The enzyme consists of a glycoside hydrolase family 43 (GH43) catalytic domain.
The purified enzyme was active towards linear |FRAME: L-Arabinans L-arabinan| and branched sugar beet arabinan, but inactive towards larch wood |FRAME: Arabinogalactan arabinogalactan|, wheat |FRAME: Arabinoxylan arabinoxylan| and |FRAME: CPD-13294|. Linear arabinan is degraded faster than branched arabinan |CITS: [15556708]|.

E215 is a key residue for AbnA hydrolytic activity. A mutant in which E215 was converted to alanine had no activity.

BSGatlas-gene-3529 "BioI is a cytochrome P450 enzyme that catalyzes C-C bond cleavage of |FRAME: ACYL-ACP| to generate |FRAME: Pimeloyl-ACPs|, a crucial intermediate for the biosynthesis of |FRAME: BIOTIN|.  The enzyme can accept a range of acyl-[acp]s, with a preference for |FRAME: Palmitoyl-ACPs ""palmitoyl-[acp]| |CITS: [11368323]|.  The proposed mechanism involves four sub-reactions, during which two oxygen atoms are incorporated at position 7 and 8 of the acyl-[acp] molecule, followed by cleavage and incorporation of a third oxygen atom to form |FRAME: 7-Oxoheptanoyl-ACPs ""7-oxoheptanoyl-[acp]""|, and its subsequent oxidation to |FRAME: Pimeloyl-ACPs ""pimeloyl-[acp]""| (it is still not clear whether the last reaction is spontaneous or catalyzed by the enzyme).  The mechanism is similar to that of |FRAME: 1.14.15.6-RXN ""EC 1.14.15.6, cholesterol monooxygenase (side-chain-cleaving)""| |CITS: [20658980]|.

The <i>bioI</i> gene was cloned and expressed in |FRAME:TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified to homogeneity.  The natural electron acceptor is not known, but the purified enzyme was active <i>in vitro</i> with cindoxin (a flavoprotein from |FRAME: TAX-57706|) in the presence of NADPH and |FRAME: FLAVONADPREDUCT-MONOMER ""flavodoxin reductase""| from |FRAME:TAX-562| |CITS: [11368323]|."

BSGatlas-gene-4173 "Burger and Glaser were the first to demonstrate transfer of glycerol phosphate from CDP-glycerol to an unknown membrane acceptor by a membrane bound CDP-glycero:poly(glycerophosphate) glycerophosphotransferase (CGPTase) |CITS: [14245357]|.

Despite the fact that several researchers were able to extract the enzyme from the membrane, it has not been purified in the next 40 years. In 1992 Pooley et al were able to link the enzyme to the |FRAME:TAX-224308| |FRAME: BSU35720| 
gene, showing that CGPTase defficiency was associated only with mutant |FRAME: BSU35720| alleles |CITS: [1309530]|.

In 2003 Schertzer and Brown cloned the |FRAME: BSU35720| gene and overexpressed it in |FRAME:TAX-562|. They were able to provide a direct biochemical evidence that this enzyme is indeed responsible for polymerization of poly(glycerol phosphate) teichoic acid |CITS: [12637499]|.

TagF shares considerable sequence similarity with |FRAME: BSU35760 TagB|. Apparently, TagB is responsible for priming the disaccharide of the linkage unit with the first glycerol-phosphate unit, while TagF is responsible for the addition of 30-40
additional glycerol-phosphate units to the chain |CITS: [11882717]|."

BSGatlas-gene-247 "Glucosamine--fructose-6-phosphate aminotransferase (GlmS) is the first enzyme of the |FRAME: UDPNAGSYN-PWY| pathway.  The <i>B. subtilis</i> enzyme has not been purified.

GlmS is essential for growth |CITS: [12682299]|.

Expression of <i>glmS</i> is repressed in response to rising glucosamine-6-phosphage (GlcN6P) concentrations, which are sensed by the 5' UTR RNA of the <i>glmS</i> transcript.  Unlike many riboswitches, binding of GlcN6P does not lead to a conformational change in the RNA |CITS: [17283212]|, but rather activates the GlcN6P-sensing ribozyme, leading to cleavage of the mRNA |CITS: [15029187]|.  This metabolite-induced cleavage targets the downstream transcript for degradation by |FRAME: BSU14530-MONOMER ""RNase J1""| |CITS: [18079181]|.

It was recently shown that the glmS riboswitch integrates both positive and negative metabolic signals |CITS: [21317896]|.

BSGatlas-gene-3464 "In E. coli ThiI is a bifunctional enzyme that is required both for the synthesis of the thiazole moiety of thiamin and for the conversion of uridine to 4-thiouridine at position 8 in tRNA. The protein is proposed to accept a sulfur from IscS-persulfide to give a ThiI-persulfide, which is subsequently used in the biosynthesis of thiazole phosphate and thiouridine |CITS: [6178725][9592144]|.

However, the B. subtilis ThiI is missing the 120-amino acid carboxy terminal domain containing the proposed redox active cysteine residue in the E. coli enzyme. 

Addition of purified ThiI protein to to a thiazole reconstitution reaction mixture did not result in any enhancement in the rate of thiazole phosphate formation |CITS: [14567704]|. Therefore, it is currently not certain whether the enzyme plays any role 
in thiazole biosynthesis in B. subtilis."

BSGatlas-gene-4385 "LipL encodes an amidotransferase that is required for lipoate biosynthesis in <i>B. subtilis</i> |CITS: [21338420][21338421]|.

The <i>lipL</i> gene was cloned with a hexahistidine-tag, expressed in <i>E. coli</i> and purified to homogeneity |CITS: [21338421]|.  The purified protein could bind up to two molecules of either |FRAME: LIPOIC-ACID| or |FRAME: CPD-195|.  These molecules do not bind to lysine residues, as they do in the lipoyl domains of 2-oxo acid dehydrogenases, but to two cysteine residues, located at positions C39 and C150.  Mutation analysis demonstrated that only C150 is essential for activity, and the authors suspect that acylation of C39 may have been an artifact.

The enzyme was shown to catalyze amidotransfer of octanoate from an octanoylated GcvH protein (the lipoate binding component of the glycine cleavage system) to the homologous component of the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex, via an octanoyl-enzyme intermediate.  It can not accept free octanoate as a substrate, and thus GcvH is a required intermediate in the lipoylation of other 2-oxo acid dehydrogenases in <i>B. subtilis</i> |CITS: [21338421]|.

One or more strains containing mutant alleles of this gene can be obtained from the <b>Bacillus Genetic Stock Center</b>.  Click <a href=""http://pasture.asc.ohio-state.edu/BGSC/index.cfm?Search=ywfL&Go=Search"">here</a> to see the list of available strains at BGSC.

BSGatlas-gene-4146 "tagTU</i> double mutant, removing IPTG from the medium resulted in gradual growth arrest, accompanied by cell morphology changes - the cells became shorter and wider with noticeable bulging, and eventually became almost round |CITS: [21964069]|.

Crystalization of a related protein from |FRAME: TAX-1313| (|FRAME: G-44730 Cps2A|), expressed without its transmembrane domain in |FRAME: TAX-562|, revealed that the protein was purified with an isopernoid phosphate lipid in its hydrophobic pocket. The enzyme behaved as a phosphotransferase, catalyzing the Mg<sup>2+</sup>-dependent hydrolysis of the diphosphate phosphoester bond and releasing orthophosphate |CITS: [21964069]|.

While purified TagT expressed without its transmembrane domain does not contain a lipid, it is able to catalyze the hydrolysis of the diphosphate phosphoester bond in an exogenously provided |FRAME: GERANYL-PP| indicating that it too is a phosphotransferase.

Based on all of these observation, it has been [roposed that the three proteins are the long-sought enzymes that catalyze the final step in wall teichoic acid biosynthesis - the transfer of the acids from their lipid anchor to the peptidoglycan |CITS: [21964069]|."

BSGatlas-gene-4162 "The <i>mnaA</i> gene of |FRAME:TAX-1423| was identified by complementation of a sphere-shaped mutant,
obtained by chemical mutagenesis |CITS: [8126437]|. The cell wall phosphate content of mutant cells was found
to be about half that of wild type, indicating a difficiency in teichoic acids |CITS: [12107153]|.

The gene was cloned into a His<sub>6</sub> expression vector, and expressed in |FRAME:TAX-562|.  The recombinant
enzyme was used <i>in vitro</i> in assays confirming its expected activity |CITS: [12107153]|."
BSGatlas-gene-4147 "The <i>tagO</i> gene of |FRAME:TAX-224308| was found downstream of the <i>tuaABCDEFGH</i> operon, which encodes the biosynthesis of teichuronic acid |CITS: [10048024]|. Homology searches matched the putative gene product with the |FRAME: GLCNACPTRANS-MONOMER| protein of |FRAME:TAX-562|, which catalyzes the activity of |FRAME: EC-2.7.8.33| activity |CITS: [1730666]|.

Attempts to produce mutants deficient in TagO in |FRAME:TAX-224308| failed, indicating that the protein is essential for that organism. However, such a mutant was constructed in |FRAME: TAX-1282|. The mutant had pleiotropic effects, including enhanced intercellular aggregation and autolytic activity, and impaired biofilm production |CITS: [21051486]|. In addition, |FRAME: TAX-1392| strains lacking tagO cannot maintain cell shape or support vegetative growth |CITS: [26324447]|.

As of today, the protein has not been purified, and its presice enzymatic activity has not been confirmed. However, placing the |FRAME:TAX-224308| gene behind a controllable promoter allowed <i>in vivo</i> characterization of its expression and activity |CITS: [12101296]|. Interference in the expression of TagO impairs the synthesis of both the major and minor teichoic acids in strain 168. Furthermore, it was shown that this enzyme also participates in the biosynthesis of teichuronic acid. The authors speculate that TagO may play a regulatory role in the balanced growth of <i>B. subtilis</i>, by shifting production of either teichoic or teicuronic acid."
BSGatlas-gene-2877 "The |FRAME: BSU24530| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423| was isolated from a chromosomal DNA library by functional complementation of an |FRAME: TAX-562| |FRAME: EG11591|-|FRAME: EG11796| double mutant strain |CITS: [20882995]|.

The gene was cloned and expressed in E. coli, and the recombinant protein was purified. Activity was tested using the Bacillus glycine cleavage system H (GcvH), a lipoate protein, as substrate.
Even though the gene resembles the |FRAME: EG11796| gene of E. coli, which encodes a |FRAME: EG11796-MONOMER ""lipoyl-protein ligase""|, this protein differs in manyt ways. First, it encodes a |FRAME: BSU24530-MONOMER|, with similar functionality to the enzyme encoded by the |FRAME: EG11591| gene of E. coli |CITS: [20882995]|. Secondly, it can only transfer the ocanoate moiety from |FRAME: Octanoyl-ACPs octanoyl-[acp]| to the H protein of the glycine-cleavage system (GcvH) |CITS: [21338421]|.

The protein acts by by forming an intermediate thioester-linked octanoyl-LipB intermediate, where the octanoyl moiety is bound to a Cys residue |CITS: [20882995]|."
BSGatlas-gene-3793 "The |FRAME: BSU32330| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423| encodes a |FRAME: BSU32330-MONOMER|, the enzyme that catalyzes the last step in the lipoate <i>de novo</i> biosynthesis pathway. The enzyme, which is S-adenosyl-L-methionine-dependent, catalyzes the insertion of sulfur atoms originating from iron-sulfur clusters within the enzyme into the carbon-6 and -8 positions of octanoate.

A mutant of |FRAME: TAX-1423| defective in the |FRAME: BSU32330| gene is ubnable to grow in a minimal medium. analysis of the E2 components of 2-oxo acid dehydrogenases from the mutant grown in a rich medium showed that most of them were not lipoylated. Complementation of the mutant with an intact |FRAME: BSU32330| gene restored lipoylation, confirming the proposed role of the enzyme |CITS: [19820084]|.

BSGatlas-gene-4178 "The |FRAME: BSU35760| gene of |FRAME:TAX-224308| was proposed to catalyze a priming reaction, attaching the first
glycerol phosphate unit to the disccharide of the teichoic acid linkage unit. This attachment is required before the |FRAME: BSU35720 TagF| polymerase can add successive glycerol phosphate units to the nascent chain. TagB has a strong sequence similarity to TagF, which has been confirmed to catalyze the polymerization reaction |CITS: [12637499]|, supports this hypothesis |CITS: [11882717]|.

The |FRAME: BSU35760| gene was cloned with a poly-His tag and expressed in |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified |CITS: [17163636]|. A substrate for the enzyme was prepared by incubating purified |FRAME: BSU35750 TagA| enzyme with a synthetic substrate that contains a synthetic 13-carbon saturated lipid chain instead of the natural 55-carbon undecaprenyl. When purified TagB protein was incubated with this substrate and CDP-glycerol, it produced the expected prduct, which was confirmed by NMR |CITS: [17163636]|."

BSGatlas-gene-1393 "The |FRAME: ThiF-Proteins ThiF| protein is involved in the posttranslational modification of |FRAME: Thi-S ThiS| by the conversion of the carboxylic acid group of the carboxyl-terminal glycine into a thiocarboxylate |CITS: [9632726]|. More specifically, ThiF catalyzes the adenylation of the carboxyl-terminal glycine of ThiS by ATP |CITS: [10382260][9632726]|. 
ThiS and ThiF form a covalently linked protein-protein conjugate as an essential intermediate of this reaction |CITS: [11438688]|.

The |FRAME: BSU11700| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423| has been cloned, expressed in E. coli and purified, and used in an <i>in vitro</i> reconstitution reaction for production of the thiazole moiety of thiamin phosphate |CITS: [14567704]|.

Unlike in E. coli, no cross-linking between |FRAME: BSU11700-MONOMER ThiF| and |FRAME: BSU11680-MONOMER ThiS| has been detected |CITS: [14567704]|."
BSGatlas-gene-1222 "The |FRAME:BSU10140| gene of the |FRAME: TAX-1423| is essential for protoheme IX biosynthesis. Mutations in the gene cause the accumulation of |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRINOGEN_III| or |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRIN_III| in the growth medium |CITS: [1459957]|.

When expressed in Escherichia coli, the enzyme oxidized |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRINOGEN_III| and |FRAME: PROTOPORPHYRINOGEN| to |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRIN_III| and |FRAME: PROTOPORPHYRIN_IX|, respectively. However, it oxidizes |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRINOGEN_III| at a rate almost nine-fold faster than it oxidizes
|FRAME: PROTOPORPHYRINOGEN| and has a lower apparent Km for the latter, resulting in an apparent specificity of about 12-fold higher |CITS: [7928957]|.

The |FRAME:BSU10140| gene has been cloned with a His tag and expressed in <i>E. coli</i>, and the recombinant protein has been purified to homogeneity |CITS: [9784236]|. While the enzyme utilizes FAD like the eukaryotic protoporphyrinogen oxidase, it differs from them in several ways. It prefers |FRAME: COPROPORPHYRINOGEN_III| as substrate, it is monomeric, while the eukaryotic enzymes are homodimeric, and it is not inhibited by diphenyl ethers such as |FRAME: ACIFLUORFEN|.

Initial reports suggested that the enzyme spans the membrane, but later work found it to be soluble. The crystal structure of the enzyme bound to |FRAME: ACIFLUORFEN| has been published |CITS: [19944166]|."
BSGatlas-gene-1442 "The biosynthesis of |FRAME: HEME_A| from |FRAME: Heme-b| is catalyzed in the membrane by two enzymes, |FRAME: BSU14880-MONOMER| and |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER|, encoded by the |FRAME: BSU14880| and |FRAME: BSU14870| genes, respectively. The genes are part of the <i>ctaBCDEF</i> locus, which encodes the biosynthesis of cytochrome c oxidase caa3 |CITS: [9829923]|.

In addition to |FRAME: BSU14880|, |FRAME: TAX-1423| contains a paralogous gene now known as |FRAME: BSU12080|. This gene was shown to complement a |FRAME: BSU14880| deletion mutant with respect to heme <i>a</i> bisynthesis, indicating it encodes an active heme <i>o</i> synthase |CITS: [10675592]|."
BSGatlas-gene-1761 "The biosynthesis of |FRAME: HEME_A| from |FRAME: Heme-b| is catalyzed in the membrane by two enzymes, |FRAME: BSU14880-MONOMER| and |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER|, encoded by the |FRAME: BSU14880| and |FRAME: BSU14870| genes, respectively. The genes are part of the <i>ctaBCDEF</i> locus, which encodes the biosynthesis of cytochrome c oxidase caa3 |CITS: [9829923]|.
Expression of the two genes in |FRAME: TAX-562|, which does not produce |FRAME: HEME_A| natrually (although it does produce |FRAME: HEME_O|), resulted in production of |FRAME: HEME_A| |CITS: [7968515]|.

A |FRAME: BSU14870| deletion mutant was found to lack both |FRAME: HEME_A| and |FRAME: HEME_O|, while a |FRAME: BSU14880| mutant produced |FRAME: HEME_O|, but lacked |FRAME: HEME_A| |CITS: [7968515]|.

|FRAME: BSU14880-MONOMER CtaB| and |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER CtaA| are known to interact with each other. It has been proposed that the two proteins form a complex and that |FRAME: HEME_O| is transferred directly from CtaB to CtaA |CITS: [15491161]|. 

|FRAME: HEME_A ""Heme a""| is derived from |FRAME: HEME_O| by two successive hydroxylations. The first hydroxylation forms |FRAME: Heme_I|, the second hydroxylation results in an unstable dihydroxymethyl group, which spontaneously decomposes into a formyl group and a water molecule |CITS: [12206660][16321940]|. However, while |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER| is strictly dependent on molecular oxygen, the source of the oxygen atom in |FRAME: HEME_A| was shown not to be molecular oxygen. It may be derived from water, but this has not been proven, and the mechanism for such a reaction is not understood |CITS: [15236569]|. In addition, it is still unknown how electrons enter the bacterial enzyme (both a thioredoxin-like protein and menaquinol have been suggested). For a review see |CITS: [22484221]|.

Several histidine residues |CITS: [16321940]| and two cysteine residues |CITS: [26592143]| have been implicated as essential for catalysis."
BSGatlas-gene-1762 "The biosynthesis of |FRAME: HEME_A| from |FRAME: Heme-b| is catalyzed in the membrane by two enzymes, |FRAME: BSU14880-MONOMER| and |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER|, encoded by the |FRAME: BSU14880| and |FRAME: BSU14870| genes, respectively. |FRAME: BSU14880-MONOMER CtaB| and |FRAME: BSU14870-MONOMER CtaA| are known to interact with each other. It has been proposed that the two proteins form a complex and that |FRAME: HEME_O| is transferred directly from CtaB to CtaA |CITS: [15491161]|. 

Heme <i>o</i> synthase catalyzes the transfer of a farnesyl group from |FRAME: FARNESYL-PP ""farnesyl diphosphate""| to the 2-vinyl group on pyrrole ring A of |FRAME: PROTOHEME|. 

The |FRAME: BSU14880| gene of |FRAME: TAX-1423| was cloned with a His<sub>7</sub> tag and expressed on |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified. The enzyme, which has eight transmembrane helices, binds substoichiometric amounts of |FRAME: Heme-b| and |FRAME: HEME_O|, which are the substrate and unreleased product, respectively. A strictly conserved His199 present at the extra-cellular side of helix 5 serves as the heme-binding site |CITS: [19204012]|."

BSGatlas-gene-494 "The enzyme, a member of the large haloacid dehalogenase (HAD) superfamily, catalyzes the essential dephosphorylation of the riboflavin precursor, |FRAME: CPD-1086| during riboflavin biosynthesis. It was purified 800-fold from a riboflavin-producing <i>B. subtilis</i> strain and the gene encoding it was identified |CITS: [26316208]|. The <i>ycsE</i> gene was then cloned and expressed in <i>E. coli</i>, and the recombinant protein was purified to homogeneity and characterized |CITS: [26316208]|.

YcsE is a relatively broad-specificity 5'-nucleotidase |CITS: [27784292]|.

BSGatlas-gene-4176 "The first committed step in the wall teichoic acid biosynthetic pathway in |FRAME: TAX-224308| is catalyzed by |FRAME: BSU35750 TagA|, which transfers |FRAME: N-acetyl-D-mannosamine| (ManNAc) to the C4 hydroxyl of a membrane-anchored |FRAME: ACETYL-D-GLUCOSAMINYLDIPHOSPHO-UNDECAPRE| (lipid I) to make |FRAME: ACETYL-ETCETERA-GLUCOSAMINYLDIPHOSPHOUND| (lipid II) (The first membrane-bound intermediate in the pathway, undecaprenyl-diphospho-N-acetylglucosamine, which is produced by |FRAME: BSU35530 TagO|, is utilized in the synthesis of several different anionic cell wall polymers).

Even though the function of TagA has been proposed early on based on data from sequence homology |CITS: [1906926]|, thermosensitive mutations |CITS: [1906926]|, and transcriptional fusions |CITS: [7952180]|, it has not been demonstrated <i>in vitro</i> until 2006.

The main difficulty is assaying the enzyme is the fact that its natural substrate contains a 55-carbon undecaprenyl chain that is embedded in the bacterial membrane. The problem was solved by synthesizing an acceptor analogue containing a 13-carbon saturated lipid chain. The |FRAME: BSU35750| gene was cloned with a poly-His tag and expressed in |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified and incubated with the synthetic substrate analogue. The enzyme, which does not contain any membrane spanning regions, does not recognize the undecaprenyl chain and thus was able to act on the analogue, forming a ManNAc-GlcNAc-pp-lipid product and confirming its predicted activity |CITS: [17163636]|."
BSGatlas-gene-1613 "The last reaction of the methionine salvage pathway is catalyzed in |FRAME: TAX-1423|, as in mammals, by a glutamine-dependent transaminase, encoded by the |FRAME: BSU13580| gene.
The gene is located in a region of the |FRAME: TAX-1423| genome encoding most of the enzymes involved in the methionine salvage pathway. 

While believed to be specific for methionine transamination, disruption of the gene had no visible effect on growth on |FRAME: CPD-560| as the sulfur source ( (on this medium the sulfur nutrition of the cells depends entirely on the methionine salvage pathway). This observation was explained by the redundant function of isozymes (up to nine amino acid transaminases are present in |FRAME: TAX-1423|) |CITS: [12022921]|. However, in a subsequent experiment, mutants were shown to grow more slowly that the wild type, and entered stationary phase at a substantially lower optical density |CITS: [24837359]|.

In a study of several amino acid transaminases from |FRAME: TAX-1423|, it was found that only MtnE (then known as YkrV) was able to convert |FRAME: CPD-479| to L-methionine, and it catalyzed the reaction only when L-glutamine was used as amino donor |CITS: [12670965]|. BSGatlas-gene-1392 "Thiazole synthase (ThiG) catalyzes a very complex reaction that produces the thiazole moiety of thiamin diphosphate.
The enzyme requires three inputs - |FRAME: DEOXYXYLULOSE-5P| (DXP), |FRAME: CPD-12279|, and |FRAME: Adenylated-ThiS-Proteins| |CITS: [14567704]|. 

Based on current understanding, the reaction starts when DXP binds to lysine 96 of the thiazole synthase, forming an imine that tautomerizes to aminoketone |CITS: [15012138]|. Addition of the ThiS-thiocarboxylate, (formed separately by reactions catalyzed by |FRAME: BSU11700 ThiF| and |FRAME: BSU29590 IscS|) is followed by an S/O acyl shift and loss of water, where the ThiS-thiocarboxylate sulfur is exchanged with an oxygen from DXP |CITS: [15489164]|.
In the next step the ThiS protein leaves the complex and |FRAME: CPD-12279| (formed by |FRAME: CPLX-8352 ThiO| from |FRAME: GLY|) is added. At this point a cyclization occurs via a transimination that involves the release of ThiG, producing the final product of the enzyme, |FRAME: CPD-13575| |CITS: [19216519]|.
"
